Â»â€¡n Ã„â€˜Ã¡ÂºÂ¡i. To&agrave; nh&agrave; BÃ†Â°u Ã„â€˜iÃ¡Â»â€¡n vÃ¡Â»â€ºi th&aacute;p Ã„â€˜Ã¡Â»â€œng hÃ¡Â»â€œ cÃ¡Â»â€¢ k&iacute;nh in b&oacute;ng hÃ¡Â»â€œ GÃ†Â°Ã†Â¡m Ã„â€˜&atilde; Ã„â€˜i v&agrave;o l&ograve;ng nhiÃ¡Â»ï¿½u ngÃ†Â°Ã¡Â»ï¿½i d&acirc;n H&agrave; NÃ¡Â»â„¢i.</span></h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7c8c8a03f71_crop.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>CÃ¡ÂºÂ§u Th&ecirc; H&uacute;c dÃ¡ÂºÂ«n v&agrave;o Ã„ï¿½Ã¡Â»ï¿½n NgÃ¡Â»ï¿½c SÃ†Â¡n</em></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">NgÃ†Â°Ã¡Â»ï¿½i d&acirc;n H&agrave; NÃ¡Â»â„¢i sÃ¡Â»â€˜ng Ã¡Â»Å¸ khu vÃ¡Â»Â±c quanh hÃ¡Â»â€œ c&oacute; th&oacute;i quen ra Ã„â€˜&acirc;y tÃ¡ÂºÂ­p thÃ¡Â»Æ’ dÃ¡Â»Â¥c v&agrave;o s&aacute;ng sÃ¡Â»â€ºm, Ã„â€˜Ã¡ÂºÂ·c biÃ¡Â»â€¡t l&agrave; v&agrave;o m&ugrave;a h&egrave;. HÃ¡Â»ï¿½ gÃ¡Â»ï¿½i c&aacute;c khu phÃ¡Â»â€˜ nÃ¡ÂºÂ±m quanh hÃ¡Â»â€œ l&agrave; BÃ¡Â»ï¿½ HÃ¡Â»â€œ.<br /><br />Th&aacute;p B&uacute;t (hay l&agrave; b&uacute;t th&aacute;p) nÃ¡ÂºÂ±m Ã¡Â»Å¸ cÃ¡ÂºÂ¡nh hÃ¡Â»â€œ, Ã„â€˜Ã¡Â»â€˜i vÃ¡Â»â€ºi Ã„â€˜&agrave;i nghi&ecirc;n nÃ¡ÂºÂ±m Ã¡Â»Å¸ bÃ¡Â»ï¿½ hÃ¡Â»â€œ. MÃ¡Â»â€”i ng&agrave;y, b&oacute;ng cÃ¡Â»Â§a Th&aacute;p b&uacute;t ngÃ¡ÂºÂ£ xuÃ¡Â»â€˜ng chÃ¡ÂºÂ¥m mÃ¡Â»Â±c trong Ã„â€˜&agrave;i nghi&ecirc;n, tÃ¡ÂºÂ¡o th&agrave;nh mÃ¡Â»â„¢t biÃ¡Â»Æ’u tÃ†Â°Ã¡Â»Â£ng rÃ¡ÂºÂ¥t Ã„â€˜Ã¡ÂºÂ¹p cho hÃ¡Â»ï¿½c vÃ¡ÂºÂ¥n: "Th&aacute;p B&uacute;t - Ã„â€˜&agrave;i nghi&ecirc;n - Ã„â€˜Ã¡Â»ï¿½ thÃ†Â¡ l&ecirc;n trÃ¡Â»ï¿½i xanh"<br /><br />Chu vi s&aacute;t bÃ¡Â»ï¿½ hÃ¡Â»â€œ l&agrave; khoÃ¡ÂºÂ£ng 1750m, c&ograve;n chu vi Ã„â€˜Ã†Â°Ã¡Â»ï¿½ng xe cÃ†Â¡ giÃ¡Â»â€ºi Ã„â€˜i v&ograve;ng quanh hÃ¡Â»â€œ l&agrave; khoÃ¡ÂºÂ£ng 2000m.</p>', 'Wikipedia', '', '13:44:32', 1, 'admin');
INSERT INTO news_article_revision (revision_id, article_id, category_id, title, sub_title, slug, description, content, author, icons, created_date, created_user_id, created_user_name) VALUES (24, 9, 4, 'One Pillar Pagoda', '', 'one-pillar-pagoda', '<p>The One Pillar Pagoda (Vietnamese: Ch&ugrave;a MÃ¡Â»â„¢t CÃ¡Â»â„¢t, formally Di&ecirc;n HÃ¡Â»Â±u tÃ¡Â»Â± Ã¥Â»Â¶Ã§Â¥ï¿½Ã¥Â¯Âº or Li&ecirc;n Hoa Ã„ï¿½&agrave;i Ã¨â€œÂ®Ã¨Å Â±Ã¨â€¡Âº) is a historic Buddhist temple in Hanoi, the capital of Vietnam. It is regarded alongside the Perfume Temple, as one of Vietnam''s two most iconic temples.</p>', '<h2 style="text-align: justify;"><span id="History" class="mw-headline">History</span></h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The temple was built by Emperor L&yacute; Th&aacute;i T&ocirc;ng, who ruled from 1028 to 1054. According to the court records, L&yacute; Th&aacute;i T&ocirc;ng was childless and dreamt that he met the bodhisattva Avalokiteshvara, who handed him a baby son while seated on a lotus flower. L&yacute; Th&aacute;i T&ocirc;ng then married a peasant girl that he had met and she bore him a son. The emperor constructed the temple in gratitude for this in 1049, having been told by a monk named ThiÃ¡Â»ï¿½n TuÃ¡Â»â€¡ to build the temple, by erecting a pillar in the middle of a lotus pond, similar to the one he saw in the dream.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7ca50b95de3_crop.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>One Pillar Pagoda, Hanoi</em></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The temple was located in what was then the T&acirc;y CÃ¡ÂºÂ¥m Garden in ThÃ¡ÂºÂ¡ch BÃ¡ÂºÂ£o, VÃ„Â©nh ThuÃ¡ÂºÂ­n district in the capital ThÃ„Æ’ng Long (now known as Hanoi). Before the pagoda was opened, prayers were held for the longevity of the monarch. During the L&yacute; Dynasty era, the temple was the site of an annual royal ceremony on the occasion of Vesak, the birthday of Gautama Buddha. A Buddha-bathing ceremony was held annually by the monarch, and it attracted monks and laymen alike to the ceremony. The monarch would then free a bird, which was followed by the people.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img src="http://phuocnh/amancms/upload/news/admin/2010/08/4c7ca50c97cd8_crop.JPG" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Steps leading up to the pagoda</em></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The temple was renovated in 1105 by Emperor L&yacute; Nh&acirc;n T&ocirc;ng and a bell was cast and an installation was attempted in 1109. However, the bell, which was regarded as one of the four major capital works of Vietnam at the time, was much too large and heavy, and could not be installed. Since it could not be tolled while left on the ground, it was moved into the countryside and deposited in farmland adjacent to NhÃ¡ÂºÂ¥t TrÃ¡Â»Â¥ Temple. This land was widely inhabited by turtles, so the bell came to be known as Q<strong>uy Ã„ï¿½iÃ¡Â»ï¿½n chung</strong>, which means Bell of the Turtle Farmland. At the start of the 15th century, Vietnam was invaded and occupied by the Ming Dynasty. In 1426, the future Emperor L&ecirc; LÃ¡Â»Â£i attacked and dispersed the Chinese forces, and while the Ming were in retreat and low on weapons, their commanding general ordered that the bell be smelted, so that the copper could be used for manufacturing weaponry.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The temple is built of wood on a single stone pillar 1.25 m in diameter, and it is designed to resemble a lotus blossom, which is a Buddhist symbol of purity, since a lotus blossoms in a muddy pond. In 1954, the French Union forces destroyed the pagoda before withdrawing from Vietnam after the First Indochina War, It was rebuilt afterwards.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">A replica was built in ThÃ¡Â»Â§ Ã„ï¿½Ã¡Â»Â©c in Saigon in the late 1950s and early 1960s.</p>', 'Wikipedia', '', '13:46:37', 1, 'admin');
